kernel_variant.question:
Let A be a finite set with |A| \ge 3 and let S be a collection of ordered triples (a,b,c) of pairwise distinct elements of A such that

1. (cyclic invariance) (a,b,c) \in S \;\Longleftrightarrow\; (b,c,a) \in S;
2. (reversal / asymmetry) (a,b,c) \in S \;\Longrightarrow\; (c,b,a) \notin S;
3. (four-term exchange) for every four distinct a,b,c,d \in A
   (a,b,c),(c,d,a) \in S \;\Longleftrightarrow\; (b,c,d),(d,a,b) \in S;
4. (totality) for every three distinct a,b,c \in A exactly one of the two triples (a,b,c) and (c,b,a) belongs to S.

Prove that there exists an injective map g:A \to \mathbb R such that for all distinct a,b,c \in A

g(a)<g(b)<g(c)\qquad\Longrightarrow\qquad(a,b,c)\in S.
(The converse implication is not required.)
